<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="What_are_limits.3F">What are limits?</span></h2>
<p>A limit is the value that a function or sequence "approaches" as the input or index approaches some value. Limits are an essential part of calculus (and mathematical analysis in general), and are used to define <a href="/wiki/index.php/Calc1:Continuity" title="Calc1:Continuity">continuity</a>, <a href="/wiki/index.php?title=Calc1:Derivatives&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Calc1:Derivatives (page does not exist)">derivatives</a>, and <a href="/wiki/index.php?title=Calc1:Integrals&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Calc1:Integrals (page does not exist)">integrals</a>.</p>
<p>In formulas, limit is usually abbreviated as lim as in lim(an) = a, and the fact of approaching a limit is represented by the right arrow (→) as in an → a.</p>
